Implementation of Machine Learning to Determine the Best Employees

Introduction

In businesses, finding and keeping the best employees is key to success. This project aims to build a system that predicts which employees are the best based on their performance and other factors. We used a dataset with information about employees and tested several machine learning methods, including Decision Trees, Random Forest, K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), and XGBoost. By comparing these methods, we want to find out which one works best for predicting employee performance.

Brief Overview of My Research Paper

In this research, we evaluated various machine learning methods to identify the best employees based on their performance. We tested Decision Trees, Random Forests, K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), and XGBoost, using cross-validation to ensure robust results. The dataset used came from IBM Analytics, featuring 29 attributes and around 22,005 samples. Among the methods tested, Random Forest achieved the highest accuracy of 99.89% on test data, making it the most effective for this task. XGBoost also performed very well with an accuracy of 99.81%. Decision Trees and KNN showed lower accuracy compared to these models. The study highlights Random Forest as the top-performing model and suggests future research could explore dataset imbalances to further enhance model accuracy.

Outlier Detection and Removal

The Interquartile Range (IQR) method is used to detect outliers. Outliers are values lying outside 1.5 times the IQR above the third quartile (Q3) or below the first quartile (Q1).

In[]:
Q1 = df[numerical_variables].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df[numerical_variables].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

outliers = ((df[numerical_variables] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (df[numerical_variables] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR))).sum()
print("Number of outliers detected by IQR method:\n ", outliers)

Handling Outliers by Replacing Them with NaN

In[]:
# Calculate Q1, Q3, and IQR
Q1 = df[numerical_variables].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df[numerical_variables].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Define outliers as values below Q1 - 1.5*IQR or above Q3 + 1.5*IQR
outliers_lower = df[numerical_variables] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)
outliers_upper = df[numerical_variables] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)

# Replace outliers with NaN
df[numerical_variables] = df[numerical_variables].mask(outliers_lower | outliers_upper)

Outliers identified in the previous step are replaced with NaN. This allows us to later impute these values using suitable techniques.

Missing Values Imputation

Imputing Missing Values with MissForest

MissForest is a random forest imputation algorithm for missing data. It initially imputes all missing data using the mean/mode, then for each variable with missing values, MissForest fits a random forest on the observed part and then predicts the missing part. This process of training and predicting repeats in an iterative process until a stopping criterion is met, or a maximum number of user-specified iterations is reached.

We use the MissForest algorithm to impute missing values in both categorical and numerical columns. This method is effective in preserving the data structure during imputation.

In[]:
df[categorical_variables] = df[categorical_variables].astype('category')
In[]:
imputer_mixed = MissForest()

df2 = imputer_mixed.fit_transform(df, categorical=categorical_variables)

2. Random Forest Classifier

A Random Forest is an ensemble learning method that combines multiple decision trees to improve the model's accuracy and robustness. Each tree is trained on a random subset of the data and features, and the final prediction is made by averaging the predictions of all trees (for regression) or by majority vote (for classification).

3. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) Classifier

4. XGBoost Classifier

XGBoost is a powerful, scalable machine learning algorithm that uses the gradient boosting framework. It builds an ensemble of weak learners (typically decision trees) sequentially, where each new tree attempts to correct the errors made by the previous trees. XGBoost is known for its high performance and efficiency in handling large datasets.

The cross-validation results for the XGBoost (XGBClassifier) model demonstrate exceptional performance with accuracy scores ranging from 0.9966 to 0.9989 across the 5 folds. The mean accuracy across all folds is approximately 0.9979, indicating that the XGBoost model accurately predicts the target variable about 99.79% of the time.

These results highlight the strong predictive power of the XGBoost classifier, which consistently performs with very high accuracy across different subsets of the training data. The narrow range of accuracy scores across the folds suggests that the model is robust and less sensitive to variations in the data, showing that XGBoost is capable of maintaining its performance even with different training and testing splits. This level of accuracy suggests that XGBoost is highly effective for this classification task, making it one of the best-performing models in terms of both accuracy and consistency. Overall, the XGBoost classifier offers a reliable and powerful approach for achieving high classification accuracy in this context.

Decision Tree Classifier
The Decision Tree Classifier correctly predicted 99.52% of the cases in the test data. It did a great job with both classes, almost perfectly identifying them. It made a few mistakes: 6 times it confused class 0 with class 1 and 7 times it confused class 1 with class 0. Overall, it's very accurate but slightly less so compared to some other models.

Random Forest Classifier
The Random Forest Classifier was the most accurate, with 99.89% correct predictions. It did an excellent job with both classes, making no mistakes in predicting class 1 and only confusing 3 class 0 cases as class 1. This model is very reliable and handles the data well, thanks to its combination of multiple decision trees.

KNN Classifier
The K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) Classifier had an accuracy of 98.66%. It performed well but was not as precise with class 0 as the other models, misclassifying 36 class 0 cases as class 1. While it did a good job with class 1, it made more errors with class 0 compared to the other models.

XGBoost Classifier
The XGBoost Classifier achieved 99.81% accuracy. It performed very well, making only 4 mistakes with class 0 and 1 mistake with class 1. It handled the data effectively and had high accuracy with both classes, showing that its a strong model for this task.

Conclusion

Model Training Accuracy (Cross-Validation) Test Accuracy

In the research for predicting the best employee using machine learning algorithms, the Random Forest Classifier stands out as the most effective model. It achieved a remarkable accuracy of 99.82% on the training data and 99.89% on the test data. This high accuracy demonstrates the model's exceptional performance in identifying top candidates and its strong ability to generalize from training to new, unseen data. The Random Forest Classifiers robust performance and consistency make it the best choice for this prediction task, ensuring reliable and precise identification of the best employees.
